name":"Ferg","meanings":["German: occupational name for a ferryman, Middle High German <i>verje</i>, <i>verge</i>."]}]},{"name":"Griffin","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Welsh: from the personal name <i>Gruffin, Griffin</i>, a pet form of Middle Welsh <i>Gruffudd</i>. In the Welsh border counties this name was introduced directly from Welsh, and in the eastern counties of England by Bretons from France who came over with the Norman conquest.","Irish: Anglicized (part translated) form of Gaelic <b>Ó Gríobhtha</b> ‘descendant of <i>Gríobhtha</i>’, a personal name from <i>gríobh</i> ‘gryphon’."],"variants":[{"name":"Griffing","meanings":["Variant of   Griffin  ."]},{"name":"Griffee","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Gríobhtha</b> (see   Griffin  )."]},{"name":"Griffy","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Gríobhtha</b> (see   Griffin  )."]},{"name":"Griffey","meanings":["Irish (Clare): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Gríobhtha</b> (see   Griffin  )."]},{"name":"Griffen","meanings":["Irish (Cork): variant of   Griffin  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret ferch Griffin was born as the daughter of Baron Griffin ap Kiddy and Lady Griffin ap Kiddy. She had at least 1 son with Rhys ap Gronwy."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","1246–1263":"1246–1263","1163–Male":"1163–Surnud","1173–Female":"1173–Surnud","1246":"1246","1263":"1263","1163":"1163","1173":"1173","1270":"1270","Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1270–Male":"1270–Kuollut","1246–1263":"1246–1